  "text": "The deployment spec change to Pod creation chain in Kubernetes v1.32.0 follows these key steps:\n\n1. **Deployment Controller Reconcile** (pkg/controller/deployment/deployment_controller.go:590): The DeploymentController.syncDeployment() method is invoked when a Deployment spec changes. This is the entry point of the reconciliation loop that watches Deployments.\n\n2. **ReplicaSet Creation** (pkg/controller/deployment/sync.go:138-224): The DeploymentController.getNewReplicaSet() function creates a new ReplicaSet. At line 224, it calls dc.client.AppsV1().ReplicaSets(d.Namespace).Create() to create the ReplicaSet object via the Kubernetes API client.\n\n3. **ReplicaSet Controller Reconcile** (pkg/controller/replicaset/replica_set.go:675): Once the ReplicaSet is created, the ReplicaSetController.syncReplicaSet() method is invoked. This reconciliation loop watches ReplicaSets and ensures the desired number of Pods are created.\n\n4. **Pod Creation Logic** (pkg/controller/replicaset/replica_set.go:569): The ReplicaSetController.manageReplicas() method determines how many Pods need to be created or deleted to match the desired replica count. At line 598, it calls rsc.podControl.CreatePods() to initiate Pod creation.\n\n5. **Pod Creation in Controller** (pkg/controller/controller_utils.go:530): The RealPodControl.CreatePods() method (line 530) is the actual implementation of Pod creation. It calls GetPodFromTemplate() to create a Pod object, then invokes r.KubeClient.CoreV1().Pods(namespace).Create() to create the Pod via the Kubernetes API client (line 582).\n\n6. **API Server Pod Storage** (pkg/registry/core/pod/storage/storage.go:72): The NewStorage() function sets up the REST storage handler for Pods in the API server. It creates a genericregistry.Store with Pod-specific strategies and options. This handler receives the Pod creation request from the client.\n\n7. **Pod Validation and Preparation** (pkg/registry/core/pod/strategy.go:86): The podStrategy.PrepareForCreate() method prepares the Pod object for storage in the API server. It performs validation and any necessary transformations before the Pod is persisted to the backing store (typically etcd).\n\nThis chain demonstrates the hierarchical control relationship: Deployment → ReplicaSet → Pod, where each controller level manages the next level through API-driven reconciliation loops."
